---------------------------------------------------------------------

Required datasets

Create three deterministic stress datasets.

### deep_paths

Directory depth ≥ 20 levels.

Example pattern:
/a/b/c/d/e/f/g/h/i/j/k/l/m/n/o/p/q/r/s/t/fileX.bin


Include:

- 200–500 files
- path lengths between 120–260 characters

---

### long_names

Very long filenames (100–200 characters).

Structure:
dataset/
very_long_filename_...._001.bin


Include:

- 200 files
- average name length ≥ 120 characters

---

### fragmentation_heavy

Simulate files split into many extents.

Dataset characteristics:

- 20 large files
- forced extent splitting to produce ≥ 40 extents per file
- moderate path length

---

### mixed_worst_case

Combine all characteristics:

- deep paths
- long names
- forced fragmentation

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Required archive variants

Run comparisons using:

- payload_only
- extent_identity_only
- extent_identity_inline_path

Optional comparison:

- payload_plus_manifest

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Required output

Produce:
format12_stress_summary.json
format12_stress_summary.md


Metrics required:

- archive_byte_size
- overhead_vs_payload_only
- overhead_vs_extent_identity_only
- average_path_length
- total_extent_count
- extents_per_file_distribution

Also compute:
bytes_added_per_character_of_path
bytes_added_per_extent


---------------------------------------------------------------------

Evaluation questions

The summary must answer:

1. Does inline path duplication cause >20% archive expansion under worst-case conditions?
2. Is inline naming still significantly smaller than manifest-based approaches?
3. Does fragmentation multiply path duplication cost beyond acceptable limits?

---------------------------------------------------------------------

CLI requirement

Add a comparison command:
run-format12-stress-comparison


Verify:
cargo run -p crushr --bin crushr-lab-salvage -- run-format12-stress-comparison --help


